data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code uses the **timeout enforcement** pattern — it aborts a thread that exceeds a time limit. It also catches `ThreadAbortException` with `ResetAbort` (control flow pattern).

**Why this breaks on .NET 8:** `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. There is no way to forcibly kill a managed thread.

### The fundamental shift

.NET Framework used **preemptive** cancellation (runtime injects an exception). Modern .NET requires **cooperative** cancellation (code must voluntarily check and respond).

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always wrap in using.
        // CancelAfter arms a timer that fires Cancel() after the timeout.
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run schedules work on the thread pool (no manual Thread needed).
            // WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException if the token fires
            // before the task completes — this is the .NET 6+ timeout primitive.
            return Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token)
                       .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                       .GetAwaiter()
                       .GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running, it must cooperate

The code above will throw `TimeoutException` promptly, but **the work delegate keeps running in the background** until it finishes or hits a checkpoint. This is the key behavioral difference from `Thread.Abort`.

To make work actually stop, accept and check a `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(token), token)
                   .WaitAsync(token)
                   .GetAwaiter()
                   .GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example — work cooperates by checking the token:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is cooperative. If `work` never checks the token, it runs to completion in the background even after you throw `TimeoutException`. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always use `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use the `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Blocking calls ignore the token** | `Thread.Sleep`, raw socket reads, etc. won't respond to cancellation. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O overloads. |
| **`Task.Run` + `.Result` can deadlock on UI/ASP.NET sync contexts** | If callers have a `SynchronizationContext`, prefer `async Task<T>` all the way up. |

### API Mapping

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` or `Task.WhenAny` |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` and decide |
